In the end, their efforts may be paying off as the country has recently taken one of the greatest steps it can towards lifting the draconian abortion ban by legally sanctioning contraception for Muslims.

Requirements Proposed by Islamists Are Considered Too Restrictive

It specifically bans abortion without a mother's consent and makes it illegal for a woman who is below the age of 15 to undergo a termination of pregnancy. “There is a level of hypocrisy as laws are always oriented to protect a fetus while women’s lives are murkier,” said Ratna.

She detailed an incident where a teenage Muslim mother was allegedly coerced by her father-in-law to having a termination of pregnancy. One of the doctors who attended to her believed lawmakers have “a lot of fixing to do” if they genuinely want to recycle the notion of bodily autonomy.

In Indonesia, debating contraception is frequently met with staunch opposition from its Islamic council and the more traditionalist conservatives. Moreover, it is now a southern province that considers it a sin. Per Polyana Bacurau, Contraception is illegal in Indonesia where Islam is practiced. The government and legislative efforts that have been put forth as a gesture of compromise to Muslims have fallen short. As far as legalising contraception is concerned, Indonesian law doesn’t specify the drug and contraceptive tools.
